    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"4-43\">\n<h2>4-43</h2><div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 4, Section 2: Systems of Equations: Graphs and Substitution</div><div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Builds and interprets a two-variable cost equation and identifies multiple solutions.</div>\n<p>Start by focusing on one aspect of the problem: the cost to ride the gondola. The conductor charges $\\$2$ for each yodeler and $\\$1$ for each xylophone. It costs $\\$40$ for the entire club, with instruments, to ride the gondola.</p>\n<ol type=\"a\">\n<li>Write an equation with two variables that represents this information. Be sure to define your variables.</li>\n<li>Find a combination of xylophones and yodelers that will make your equation from part (a) true. Is this the only possible combination?</li>\n<li>List five additional combinations of xylophones and yodelers that could ride the gondola if it costs $\\$40$ for the trip. With your team, decide on a good way to organize and share your list.</li>\n<li>Jon says, “I think there could be $28$ xylophones and $8$ yodelers on the gondola.” Is he correct? Use the equation you have written to explain why or why not.</li>\n<li>Helga says, “Each correct combination we found is a solution to our equation.” Is this true? Explain what it means for something to be a solution to a two-variable equation.</li>\n</ol>\n<div class=\"workspace-lg workspace\"></div>\n</section>",
