    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"Systems-of-Linear-Equations\"><h2>Systems-of-Linear-Equations</h2><div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 3, Section 1: Graphing and Elimination</div><div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Explains systems of linear equations, graphing both lines, and interpreting point of intersection as a solution.</div>\n<p>A <strong>system of linear equations</strong> is a set of two or more linear equations that are given together, such as:</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">$$\\begin{aligned}y&amp;=2x\\\\y&amp;=-3x+5\\end{aligned}$$</p>\n<p>If the equations come from a real-world context, then each variable will represent some type of quantity in both equations. To represent a system graphically, graph each equation on the same set of axes. The graph may or may not have a <strong>point of intersection</strong>.</p>\n<p>The point of intersection lies on <em>both</em> graphs, so it is a solution to <em>both</em> equations in the system. For example, the point of intersection of the two lines graphed above is $(1,2)$:</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\">$$\\begin{aligned}2&amp;=2(1)\\\\2&amp;=2\\end{aligned}\\qquad\\begin{aligned}2&amp;=-3(1)+5\\\\2&amp;=2\\end{aligned}$$</p>\n<p>For this reason, the point of intersection is sometimes called a <strong>solution to the system of equations</strong>.</p>\n</section>",
