    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"Intersection-Parallel-and-Coincide\"><h2>Intersection-Parallel-and-Coincide</h2><div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 3, Section 1: Graphing and Elimination</div><div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Summarizes one-solution, no-solution, and infinite-solution cases for systems of lines.</div>\n<p><strong>Intersection, Parallel, and Coincide</strong></p>\n<p>When two lines lie on the same flat surface (called a plane), they may <strong>intersect</strong> (cross each other) once, an infinite number of times, or never.</p>\n<p>If two lines are <strong>parallel</strong>, then they never intersect. The system of these two lines does not have a solution. Parallel lines have the same slope but different $y$-intercepts.</p>\n<p>If two lines lie exactly on top of each other, they <strong>coincide</strong>. Since coinciding lines intersect each other at all points along the line, the system has an infinite number of solutions. Both lines have the same slope and $y$-intercept.</p>\n<p>The most common case is when the two lines intersect once. The system has one solution: the point where the lines intersect, $(x,y)$.</p>\n</section>",
